There are several file formats that are used to store intermediate
results using the commad-line Neptune/Marsyas modules. With the 
exception of the audio file formats such as .wav they are all 
text based and mostly designed for interoperability with other
software in mind. For example the feature format is the one used 
by the well known Weka machine learning software (.arff format)  
and the one used for timelines can be used with the Audacity audio
editor. 

In general it is very straightforward to convert any of these formats 
to some other syntax (such as XML) that conveys the same information. 
In fact for many of them alternative formats for reading/writing are 
already provided in the main Marsyas distribution. In addition it
should be straightforward to store them associate them with user 
in some kind of database. 



List of file formats/descrptions 

1) Audio files 
2) Collection files 
3) Time-line file 
4) Feature files 
5) Marsyas plugin files 





1) Marsyas supports several audio formats both compressed and
uncompressed. Some of the supported formats require compilation 
of external libraries and are optional. The most common is the well
known Waveform Audio File Format developed by Microsoft and IBM.   
The required file extension is .wav 


2) Collection files contain lists of paths to audio files. Each file
is specified on its own line. They are used to process batches 
of files for example to extract features. Optionally collection 
files contain paths to time-lines with tabs separating the two.

processing objects (MarSystems) and their associated parameters.

many more parameters than need to be exposed to a user.

Marsyas and does not require any interpretation. Other formats 
such as JSON are supported. They are rather verbose and hard 
to read however they contain all the necessary information to run
